binding.p: Modern binding. Modern undecorated parchment over boards. , stamped: Cod. Holm. A 223. Current binding from 1977.
Original/medieval binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. Upper part of , traces of title in dark ink: de civitate d.
binding.decoNote:
Concentric sets of panels, some of which are filled with complex knotwork ornaments. These ornaments are decorated with rope patterns. The centre panel contains a geometrical star-like pattern. Many of the tooled elements were gilded. Traces of the gold remain. The bookbinder notes that if the preserved binding is contemporary with the text, then it is one of the oldest preserved examples of gold stamped decoration on leather binding. Hobson states that the star-pattern is the only known western gilt binding derived from the Mamluk geometrical style (cf Hobson (1989)
).
binding.condition: The original binding was renovated in 1850 and removed in 1977. It is now stored separately from the manuscript. The leather is very worn, faded, and riddled with wormholes. , remains of four clasps with scallop-shaped brass rivets and red cloth inserts. , remains of nails and labels. The images to illustrate the different steps and results of the rebinding process.

history.provenance:
According to Hobson (1989)
, Albinia De la Mare suggests that the manuscript might be Venetian based on the decoration, but in a letter to librarian Harry Järv de la Mare guessses at a Florentine provenance (letter from 3 May 1967). On there is a coat of arms which according to Hedlund (1980)
belongs to the Dusmet family. However, this family does not seem to be established in Italy until the 18th century. On there are some faint traces of text, now completely illegible. In these notes were photographed and deciphered by a doc. Bäckström. His reading was: Hunc Augustinum De ciuitate dei donauit reverendissimus domnus Baptista de Lignane patauiensis episcopus concondiensis congregationi regularium canonicorum lateranensium ut inprimis sit ad usum studiosorum anno ?Sancti Johannis pro eius anima deuote precare memineritis?. (The final part of the transcritpion is incomplete.)
Baptista de Legnano, also known as Joannes Baptista Legname was bishop of Concordia 1443-55.

In Sweden the manuscript is first attested in Jaches's catalogue of 1695 and that of 1698: nr 25, U 118; 193, U 122. The note on K.B. 1734 n. 19 in folio Theol refers to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e).
